gnant and non‐malignant), in all settings (e.g. home, hospital, and palliative care institution). The included studies were characterised by the use of any medication with a sedative effect (e.g. benzodiazepines, barbiturates, anaesthesia, opioids, antipsychotics, antihistamines, or other hypnotics) where the intention was sedation for symptom relief. Sedation may have been given continuously or intermittently, with the intention of reducing the level of consciousness to relieve symptoms. The comparator was no sedation. We included studies where the person had periods when they were drowsy but not unconscious. The primary outcomes measured quality of life or a person's well‐being, while secondary outcomes focused on symptom control and adverse effects."}
